  <generalInformation><![CDATA[<p><strong>Beginners</strong> Arosa has several beginner blue runs served by drag lifts at Tschuggen and runs back down to the village all season thanks to its high altitude. Family areas are quiet and uncrowded.</p>
<p><strong>Intermediates</strong> With so many wide open reds and relaxed blue slopes, intermediate skiers are spoilt for choice. Head to Weisshorn for long reds all the way back down to the village, to Rothorn, the area’s highest point, for spectacular views, or over to Lenzerheide for tree-lined runs down from the Piz Scalottas.</p>
<p><strong>Advanced </strong>There are 40kms of ‘back country’ runs in Arosa alone, the most popular of which are at Hörnli, and plenty of challenging black runs descending from the peaks.</p>
<p><strong>Snowboarding</strong> Arosa’s park in the Tschuggen area has rails, kickers and boxes split into three levels of difficulty, plus a minipipe. The park in Lenzerheide is more suitable for children and beginner freestylers.</p>]]></generalInformation>
